Route Processing
For each published route, the build process:

reads the GPX track points, optionally reversing the route when configured in routes.yml;
computes step distance, elevation change, grade, and bearing change between adjacent points;
converts point pairs into route segments;
enriches those segments with nearby OpenStreetMap road attributes;
enriches roadway segments with MTC pavement-condition records where a good match is available;
writes the route maps, summary tables, elevation profile, and route data files used by the Quarto site.

Distances are summed from the step distances. Elevation gain is the sum of positive elevation changes, so it depends on the source GPX elevation signal and any noise in that signal.

Climbs Map
The Climbs map is a more ride-planning-oriented view. Instead of coloring every small segment by instantaneous grade, it groups sustained climbing into sections.
The chunk detector looks for climbing runs using these defaults:

climb starts at about 3.9% grade;
hard climbing starts at 6.0% grade;
short flatter recoveries up to 700 feet can be included inside a climb;
a climb section must be longer than 0.3 miles;
the section must have at least 2.0% average or distance-weighted median grade;
medium climbs require at least 4.0% average or median grade;
hard climbs require at least 6.0% average or median grade.

The map displays one feature per contiguous climb or rest section. The “Climbs Only” table removes flat and descent periods, while “With Rest Periods” keeps the full sequence of route sections. Time estimates come from simple speed ranges by section type, so they are best read as rough planning estimates rather than predictions.
